 {"id":"bd-8jx5","title":"[SUB-EPIC-PHASE] io_uring Reactor (Linux Modern Async I/O)","description":"# Sub-Epic: io_uring Reactor

## Overview

io_uring is Linux's modern async I/O interface (kernel 5.1+), offering significant performance advantages over epoll for certain workloads.

## Why io_uring

1. **True async**: Operations complete in kernel, no syscall per I/O
2. **Batching**: Submit multiple operations with single syscall
3. **Zero-copy**: Can use registered buffers
4. **Lower latency**: Kernel polling mode avoids context switches

## Scope

This sub-epic covers:
- IoUringReactor implementing Reactor trait
- Submission/completion queue management
- Buffer registration for zero-copy
- Polled mode for latency-critical paths

## Design Decisions

### When to Use io_uring vs epoll

| Use Case | Recommended |
|----------|-------------|
| Many idle connections | epoll (lower memory) |
| High throughput file I/O | io_uring |
| Network with many small ops | io_uring (batching) |
| Compatibility (old kernels) | epoll |

### Feature Detection

```rust
fn has_io_uring() -> bool {
    // Check kernel version >= 5.1
    // Try io_uring_setup() and check for features
}
```

## Dependencies

```toml
[target.'cfg(target_os = "linux")'.dependencies]
io-uring = "0.6"  # Safe Rust wrapper
```

## Task Breakdown

1. IoUringReactor core structure
2. Submission queue management
3. Completion queue processing
4. Register/deregister implementation
5. Probing for supported operations
6. Buffer registration API
7. Polled mode option
8. Fallback to epoll on old kernels

